    {
      "id": "3c6939ae86847ddc35823c36df2ebe1c64bd3eed",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 234,
        "name": "Doug Oucharek",
        "email": "doug@cadentcomputing.com",
        "username": "Doug",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-05-14 22:17:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 9: (2 inline comments)\n\nThis change is starting some changes I would need to do for the LNet Dynamic Config project (creating /etc/init.d/lnet and having a config file).  So as to not break this future work, and to making appending functionality easier, I'd like to see two things:\n\n1- Keep Lustre and LNet as separate entities for configuration purposes (you appear to have done that)\n2- Make configuration files a common base which is easy for management software to work with.  We seem to be favouring Yaml with /proc files so can we try to move the format of config files in that direction?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 9
    },
    {
      "id": "5e42c46650efcfb26ef92bd2deb6629d3e387dfd",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 126,
        "name": "Ned Bass",
        "email": "bass6@llnl.gov",
        "username": "nedbass"
      },
      "date": "2012-05-16 17:20:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 9:\n\nHi Doug,\n\nThanks for the review.  While I haven't yet looked at yaml in detail, in principle I like the idea of using a more structured and standard config file format.  It may be a few weeks before I could start working on this, but in the meantime if you'd like to push any changes I'd be happy to review them :)\n\nNed",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 9
    },
